# Cloudflare Pages redirects file.
# Format: <source>  <destination>  <status>
# Status codes: 301 (permanent), 302 (temporary), 200 (rewrite/proxy)
#
# Populate from reference/seo-map.csv before launch.
# WordPress migrations should map every indexed URL to its new home (301).
#
# Examples:
# /about-us/        /about/           301
# /old-blog-slug/   /blog/new-slug/   301
#
# Preserve WordPress feed URL for aggregators / email tools / directories:
/feed/            /rss.xml          301
#
# Sitemap paths. We serve a Yoast-style sitemap INDEX at /sitemap-index.xml that
# fans out to real /post-sitemap.xml + /page-sitemap.xml routes (src/pages/*.xml.ts),
# so those two are NOT redirected — they exist. The only legacy aliases left to
# redirect are WP's `/sitemap.xml` and Yoast's `/sitemap_index.xml` (underscore).
/sitemap.xml         /sitemap-index.xml   301
/sitemap_index.xml   /sitemap-index.xml   301
#
# IMPORTANT: `_redirects` strips query parameters during matching + forwarding.
# For sites with heavy UTM / gclid / ad-tracking traffic, query-bearing URLs
# (e.g. `/old-page/?utm_source=email`) will redirect to the new path but DROP
# the query string — destroying attribution. For those cases use Cloudflare
# Transform Rules or Bulk Redirects (account-level) which preserve params.
# Docs: https://developers.cloudflare.com/rules/transform/url-rewrite/
#
# WP /wp-content/uploads/ assets accumulate backlinks too — map them, not just
# HTML pages. Keeping original filenames preserves the backlink graph:
# /wp-content/uploads/2023/*.jpg  /images/legacy/2023/:splat.jpg  301
# /wp-content/uploads/2024/*.pdf  /documents/:splat.pdf            301
# /wp-content/uploads/*           /images/legacy/:splat            301
#
# Cloudflare Pages limits: 2,100 lines. For larger maps, use Bulk Redirects
# at the Cloudflare account level instead.
# Docs: https://developers.cloudflare.com/pages/configuration/redirects/

# --- Add WP→Astro redirects below this line ---

# AMP variants: the live WP AMP plugin exposes a /amp/ twin of every page+post
# (homepage emits <link rel="amphtml" href="…/amp/">; /about/amp/, /listings/amp/,
# /<post>/amp/ all return 200 and are indexed). The Astro rebuild emits no AMP, so
# 301 every old AMP URL to its canonical to preserve accumulated signals/links.
# Greedy single :splat maps /about/amp/ -> /about/ and nested /a/b/amp/ -> /a/b/.
/amp/        /          301
/*/amp/      /:splat/    301

# Per-page + comments RSS feeds. The root /feed/ rule above only matches the exact
# root; WP also serves /about/feed/, /contact/feed/, /listings/feed/, /<post>/feed/,
# and /comments/feed/ (all 200 live). Fold them all into the canonical feed.
/comments/feed/   /rss.xml   301
/*/feed/          /rss.xml   301

# Old WP image/asset URLs -> local copies (preserves backlinked /wp-content/uploads/
# image equity + keeps og:image / schema logo+image resolving after domain cutover).
# Referenced images are mirrored under public/images/legacy/ with original paths.
#
# Two 2015 images were mirrored as `<name>.jpg.webp` (webp bytes). A backlink to the
# ORIGINAL `.jpg` URL would otherwise hit the catch-all and 404 (no plain `.jpg` on disk).
# Map the original .jpg URLs to the existing .webp files. (More specific -> must precede
# the catch-all below.)
/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/phoenix-buying-selling-business-market-up.jpg          /images/legacy/2015/06/phoenix-buying-selling-business-market-up.jpg.webp          301
/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/phoenix-buying-selling-business-market-up-300x292.jpg   /images/legacy/2015/06/phoenix-buying-selling-business-market-up-300x292.jpg.webp   301
/wp-content/uploads/*    /images/legacy/:splat    301
